# Kubernetes and OpenShift Labeling Standards

## Overview

This rule defines labeling and annotation conventions for Kubernetes and OpenShift resources in this project, following:
- [Kubernetes recommended labels](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/common-labels/)
- [Guidelines for Labels and Annotations for OpenShift Applications](https://github.com/redhat-developer/app-labels/blob/master/labels-annotation-for-openshift.adoc)
- [OpenShift 4.20 Topology View](https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/openshift_container_platform/4.20/html-single/building_applications/index#odc-viewing-application-composition-using-topology-view)

Labels should make resources easy to inspect with `oc get`, useful in the OpenShift Topology view, and traceable back to the demo step that created them.

## Required Kubernetes labels

All workload and operator resources should include these labels when the target kind supports labels:

| Label | Status | Purpose | Example |
|-------|--------|---------|---------|
| `app.kubernetes.io/part-of` | Recommended | Groups resources by platform capability | `maas` |
| `app.kubernetes.io/name` | Recommended | Identifies the component name | `rhods-operator` |
| `app.kubernetes.io/component` | Recommended | Identifies the component role | `operator` |
| `app.kubernetes.io/instance` | Recommended | Unique instance name when different from `name` | `rhods-operator-step-01` |
| `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by` | Recommended | Tool managing the resource | `argocd` |

Label values must be under 63 characters and valid per Kubernetes label syntax rules.

## Optional Kubernetes labels

| Label | Purpose | Example |
|-------|---------|---------|
| `app.kubernetes.io/version` | Product or component version when stable and meaningful | `"8.1"`, `"1.9"` |
| `demo.rhoai.io/step` | Demo step number for resources where step tracing helps | `"05"` |

Do not hardcode a version label unless the manifest really owns that version. Operator-managed operands often change versions through CSVs or operator reconciliation.

## Values for `app.kubernetes.io/part-of`

Use short functional group names, not step numbers:

| Group | Value | Resources |
|-------|-------|-----------|
| RHOAI Platform | `rhoai-platform` | RHOAI operator, DataScienceCluster, DSCInitialization, dashboard resources |
| GPU Infrastructure | `gpu-infra` | NFD, NVIDIA GPU Operator, MachineSets, GPU node setup Jobs |
| LLM Serving | `llm-serving` | KServe, vLLM, llm-d, ServingRuntime, InferenceService |
| Model-as-a-Service | `maas` | MaaS gateway, model references, external model registration, gateway auth |
| Dev Spaces | `devspaces` | Dev Spaces operator, CheCluster, DevWorkspaces, workspace bootstrapping |
| MTA Modernization | `mta-modernization` | MTA operator, Tackle, Developer Lightspeed, MTA seed/configuration Jobs |
| Developer Hub | `developer-hub` | RHDH operator, Backstage CR, catalog/configuration resources |
| Identity | `identity` | OAuthClient, Keycloak/OIDC integration resources |
| Observability | `observability` | Dashboards, ServiceMonitors, Grafana data sources, demo monitoring links |
| GitOps | `gitops` | AppProject, Argo CD configuration, app-of-apps resources |

Add a new value only when a resource does not fit one of these groups.

## Values for `app.kubernetes.io/component`

Use standard values from the Red Hat app-labels guide where possible, extended with demo-specific roles:

| Value | Description | Examples in this demo |
|-------|-------------|----------------------|
| `operator` | Operator subscription and operator configuration | RHOAI, Dev Spaces, MTA, RHDH operators |
| `inference` | Model-serving endpoint or runtime | InferenceService, ServingRuntime, vLLM |
| `gateway` | API gateway or model access endpoint | MaaS gateway |
| `auth` | Authentication or authorization integration | OAuthClient, Authorino, Keycloak config Jobs |
| `backend` | API or control-plane service | MTA Hub, RHDH backend |
| `frontend` | User-facing UI | MTA UI, RHDH UI, dashboard resources |
| `database` | Data persistence | Postgres, MariaDB, MTA DB |
| `workspace` | Developer workspace or workspace template | DevWorkspace |
| `job` | One-shot or sync hook automation | PostSync patch/seed Jobs |
| `monitoring` | Observability components | ServiceMonitor, dashboards |

## OpenShift-specific labels

These labels improve the OpenShift Console Topology view:

| Label | Status | Purpose | Example |
|-------|--------|---------|---------|
| `app.openshift.io/runtime` | Recommended | Displays a recognizable runtime icon in Topology | `java`, `nodejs`, `python`, `postgresql` |
| `app.openshift.io/runtime-version` | Optional | Runtime version display | `"17"`, `"20"` |

## OpenShift-specific annotations

| Annotation | Status | Purpose | Example |
|------------|--------|---------|---------|
| `app.openshift.io/connects-to` | Optional | Draws dependency arrows in Topology | `'["maas-gateway"]'` |
| `app.openshift.io/vcs-uri` | Recommended | Links component to source code from Topology view | `https://github.com/adnan-drina/rhoai3-coding-demo.git` |
| `app.openshift.io/vcs-ref` | Optional | Branch, tag, or commit SHA for source link | `main` |

## RHOAI dashboard annotations

ServingRuntime resources created through GitOps must include the annotations required for the OpenShift AI dashboard to render the runtime correctly:

| Annotation | Purpose | Example |
|------------|---------|---------|
| `opendatahub.io/template-name` | Links to the platform template | `vllm-cuda-runtime` |
| `opendatahub.io/template-display-name` | Display name in Dashboard | `vLLM CUDA Runtime` |
| `opendatahub.io/apiProtocol` | Protocol indicator | `REST` |

To find platform templates:

```bash
oc get template -n redhat-ods-applications --no-headers -o custom-columns='NAME:.metadata.name'
```

## Example

```yaml
metadata:
  labels:
    app.kubernetes.io/name: mta
    app.kubernetes.io/instance: mta
    app.kubernetes.io/version: "8.1"
    app.kubernetes.io/component: operator
    app.kubernetes.io/part-of: mta-modernization
    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: argocd
    demo.rhoai.io/step: "05"
  annotations:
    app.openshift.io/vcs-uri: https://github.com/adnan-drina/rhoai3-coding-demo.git
```

## Argo CD Application labels

Argo CD Application objects in `gitops/argocd/app-of-apps/` use a separate label set from workload resources:

```yaml
metadata:
  labels:
    app.kubernetes.io/part-of: rhoai3-coding-demo
    demo.rhoai.io/step: "XX"
```

These labels group all demo Applications in the Argo CD UI. Do not use workload `part-of` values like `maas` or `developer-hub` on Application objects.

## Anti-patterns

- Step numbers in `app.kubernetes.io/part-of`, such as `step-01-rhoai-platform`
- Generic values, such as `app`, `demo`, or `platform`, when a specific capability exists
- Overly long values, such as `rhoai-platform-operator-subscription-config`
- Version labels that drift from the operator-managed installed version

## Agent behavior

When adding a manifest:
- Add labels where the resource kind supports them.
- Use an existing `part-of` value unless a new platform capability is being introduced.
- Keep labels consistent across related Namespace, Subscription, CR, Service, Route, and Job resources.
- If labels affect README diagrams, OpenShift Console screenshots, or validation selectors, update those docs/scripts together.

